Title: Peace Talks (The Dresden Files, #16)
Author: Jim Butcher
My Review:
Well, Dresden is back. It's been a few years, but Harry Dresden is still the same.

There's action, there are jokes that make you laugh out loud, there's Harry being so stubborn it hurts, and there are women who are all described as dripping with sex appeal. So if you've been with the series and liked the ride until now, don't worry, things are right where we left them.

A frustration is that this doesn't feel like a whole book. It feels like half a book. There is the whole arc of "we learn of Harry's current situation", "shit hits the fan", "Harry gets in over his head" and "Harry has a show-down". But we're left hanging in between two action scenes and more significantly, the major triggering event of this book, Thomas getting captured, remains kind of unresolved. It's not the neat and fantastic package that was Skin Game, which set my expectations quite high.

But it's the page-turner that I expected. I had fun.

Title: Legion (Legion, #1)
Author: Brandon Sanderson
My Review:
A very solid read by Sanderson, as always. A fascinating concept.
Rather too fascinating, actually.
The reason this one isn't getting the full 5 stars is that I really feel like Sanderson took on more than he could chew in this one, considering the work's length. It reads like the introduction to a full-length novel, not a novella.

Title: Hrafnsauga (Þriggja heima saga, #1)
Author: Kjartan Yngvi Björnsson
My Review:
Langt síðan ég hef skemmt mér jafn vel yfir íslenskri bók. Einföld en sannfærandi heimssköpun sem ég hef ekki séð áður, og það sprottið upp úr þeim frekar vel plægða akri sem fantasíubókum er sáð í á 21. öldinni. Skemmtileg íslensk orðanotkun á köflum. Hefði viljað láta koma mér meira á óvart, Monomyth-þræðinum fylgt heldur vel.
Bíð spenntur eftir næstu.
